    pandas

    Pandas¶

    Pandas is an open-source package used for data manipulation and data analysis. It is powerful for manipulating data structures in tables or times series. Pandas is built on top of Numpy, another python package, that is highly efficient in mathematical operations. In this notebook we will follow the CRUD operations - Create, Read, Update, and Delete - to summarize all the most basic functionalities of Pandas.

    The data used in this notebook is the stock price of Apple Inc. downloaded from Yahoo Finance.

    Table of Contents¶

    • Install: import Pandas
    • Create
      • Create a custom dataframe: DataFrame.from_dict()
      • Open a csv file: read_csv()

    null, na, or NaN is the same value in Pandas. There is no difference.

    To check if the dataframe has any null or na, we can use the function isnull() or isna() for the respective data type.

    Set Index¶

    Replace the index column can be done with the set_index() function. The argument inplace is to state if the column that became the index will be shifted or a copy of the original.

    In [29]:
    Copied! 
    # Copy the dataframe df
date = df.copy()

# Set 'Date' column as the index column
date.set_index('Date', inplace=True)

# Show result
date.head(2)
    # Copy the dataframe df date = df.copy() # Set 'Date' column as the index column date.set_index('Date', inplace=True) # Show result date.head(2)
    Out[29]:
    Open High Low Close Adj Close Volume
    Date
    2021-03-03 124.809998 125.709999 121.839996 122.059998 121.338821 112966300
    2021-03-04 121.750000 123.599998 118.620003 120.129997 119.420219 178155000

    Condition based¶

    We can update values using a conditional based function with the apply() function.

    As example, we will create a new column called Condition. The value in the column will be based on the values of the Average column. If a value is over 150, the new value in the Condition column will be assigned with the value 1, otherwise the value be assigned into 0.

    In [36]:
    Copied! 
    # Create new column call 'Condition' based on conditional values
df['Condition'] = df['Average'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x>=150 else 0)
    # Create new column call 'Condition' based on conditional values df['Condition'] = df['Average'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x>=150 else 0)

    Delete and Save¶

    Save¶

    To save a csv we can simply use to_csv(). The new csv file will be saved at the same location where the notebook is located.

    In [38]:
    Copied! 
    # Export new csv
df.to_csv('AAPL_Updated.csv')
    # Export new csv df.to_csv('AAPL_Updated.csv')

    Alternatively, we can also export the dataframe into other formats such as json or html by using following functions

    • JSON: df.to_json()
    • HTML: df.to_html()
    In [39]:
    Copied! 
    # JSON
df.to_json('APPL_JSON.json')

# HTML
df.to_html('APPL_JSON.html')
    # JSON df.to_json('APPL_JSON.json') # HTML df.to_html('APPL_JSON.html')

    Delete¶

    To delete a dataframe we can use the command del df.

    In [40]:
    Copied! 
    # Delete dataframe
del df
    # Delete dataframe del df
